"use strict";(self["webpackChunkmiccai2023"]=self["webpackChunkmiccai2023"]||[]).push([[122],{945:function(e,a,i){i.r(a),i.d(a,{default:function(){return f}});var t=i(6768),n=i.p+"img/Prof_Jaewoo_Kang.8799212e.jpg",s=i.p+"img/Jin_Ke.f6e510f8.jpg";const o={id:"keynote"},r=(0,t.Fv)('<div class="main-title" data-v-3e9ef93a><h1 data-v-3e9ef93a>Keynote</h1><div class="main-title-deco" data-v-3e9ef93a></div></div><div id="keynotes" data-v-3e9ef93a><div id="keynote-container" data-v-3e9ef93a><div class="keynote-box" data-v-3e9ef93a><div class="keynote-title" data-v-3e9ef93a>AI-driven Drug Discovery in the LLM Era</div><div class="profile-box" data-v-3e9ef93a><img src="'+n+'" class="profile" style="object-position:top;" data-v-3e9ef93a><div class="" data-v-3e9ef93a><div class="keynote-speaker" data-v-3e9ef93a>Dr. Jaewoo Kang</div><div class="affiliation" data-v-3e9ef93a><i data-v-3e9ef93a>Korea University, Republic of Korea</i></div></div></div><div class="speaker-bio" data-v-3e9ef93a><b data-v-3e9ef93a>Abstract.</b> Large Language Models (LLMs) are emerging as transformative tools across various industries, with significant implications for healthcare and pharmaceuticals. The pharmaceutical sector, characterized by its reliance on extensive knowledge, stands to gain substantial benefits from LLMs. This presentation will delve into how LLMs can enhance productivity in drug discovery by enabling comprehensive analysis of scientific papers and patents, facilitating the generation of novel scientific hypotheses, design of novel drugs, accurate prediction of the pharmacological properties of the designed drugs, and streamlining the drafting of regulatory approval documents. Building upon the speaker&#39;s expertise in AI-driven precision medicine and drug discovery, and recent advancements in biomedically specialized LLMs, this talk will provide insights into the current state and future directions of LLMs in drug discovery. <br data-v-3e9ef93a><b data-v-3e9ef93a>Bio.</b> Dr. Jaewoo Kang is a Professor of Computer Science at Korea University (since 2006) and CEO of AIGEN Sciences (founded in 2021), where he leads AI-driven precision medicine and drug discovery efforts. His expertise is in biomedical AI, with a focus on advancing AI solutions for healthcare. He holds a Ph.D. in Computer Science from the University of Wisconsin-Madison (2003) and was previously an Assistant Professor at North Carolina State University (2003-2006). Dr. Kang has made significant contributions to biomedical AI, notably the development of BioBERT (over 7,000 citations). His research team has achieved remarkable success in global precision medicine and drug discovery challenges, securing seven wins in prestigious competitions including Dream Challenges, BioASQ, and BioCreative over the past eight years. At AIGEN Sciences, he is focused on integrating AI technologies with biomedical research to advance drug discovery and personalized medicine. </div></div><div class="keynote-box" data-v-3e9ef93a><div class="keynote-title" data-v-3e9ef93a>Why Human Clinical Expertise Remains Indispensable in AI Pathology Image Interpretation</div><div class="profile-box" data-v-3e9ef93a><img src="'+s+'" class="profile" data-v-3e9ef93a><div data-v-3e9ef93a><div class="keynote-speaker" data-v-3e9ef93a>Dr. Jing Ke</div><div class="affiliation" data-v-3e9ef93a><i data-v-3e9ef93a>Shanghai Jiao Tong University, China</i></div></div></div><div class="speaker-bio" data-v-3e9ef93a><b data-v-3e9ef93a>Abstract.</b> Despite significant advances in AI for pathology image analysis, human clinical expertise remains indispensable for ensuring accuracy, interpretability, and clinical applicability. This talk will examine the essential roles pathologists play in guiding end-to-end AI development, including how their expertise shapes dataset curation, mitigates algorithmic bias, and ensures that AI tools are aligned with real-world clinical decision-making. <br data-v-3e9ef93a><b data-v-3e9ef93a>Bio.</b> Jing Ke is a tenured associate professor at Shanghai Jiao Tong University and holds the academic title of Adjunct Senior Lecturer at the University of New South Wales. Her primary research focus is computer-assisted pathology image analysis, with more than fifty published papers in top journals and conferences, including IEEE Transactions on Medical Imaging (TMI), Medical Image Analysis (MedIA), and MICCAI. Also, Jing has extensive commercial experience in GPU technology, having worked with leading companies like AMD. She has also published over ten papers on computer architectures and parallel computing in renowned venues such as MICRO, DAC, and IPDPS., and authored a book on GPU architecture analysis. </div></div></div></div>',2),d=[r];function c(e,a,i,n,s,r){return(0,t.uX)(),(0,t.CE)("div",o,d)}var l={computed:{currentYear(){return this.$route.params.year||(new Date).getFullYear().toString()}},methods:{fetchData(){this.currentYear}},created(){this.fetchData()}},v=i(1241);const h=(0,v.A)(l,[["render",c],["__scopeId","data-v-3e9ef93a"]]);var f=h}}]);
